Doubtless Turner’s work is not free from errors, as in the case of the very old story of the breeding of t‘he Bernicle-Goose (which, however, he was most loth to credit even when assured of its truth by an Irish Divine), in his confounding of the onocrotalus with the Ardea stellaris and the Cornish with the Alpine Chough; yet these are but small blots on a very excellent treatise, which compares most favourably with other writings of his time.
